My HoM wants to do press releases and wire releases without spending $$. He says it is my job to convince publications that our product is so world-class that journalists will fight with each other to get exclusive interviews with our team.

Bhai, yeh samjhana ki duniya kaisi chalti hai bhi mera hi kaam hai kya? 

Are all HoMs from this line of thinking? I've never met a single HoM who genuinely agrees that you have to spend money to get quality returns.

text:
Someone taught me this few years back. Let me share it with you

You will find 2 different kind of HOMs/CMOs  in your company

1. Who have clear idea of how marketing happen. They would know when to have patience, when to spend money and when to get free stuff. 
2. Who will have absolutely no clue about marketing, but they are there. These wonderful folks will have unreasonable expectations from you and no budgets almost all the time. 
You can pick whoever you want to work and you want to be.


I don't know anon if this will help, but this is what it is :smile:

text:
Publications don't give a f**k about products, all they care about are stories, even more than money. Juicy, interesting stories that their readers would find interesting. They're paid to source such interesting stories. If you give them that, they won't need any money.

Ask your HoM for an angle of what this story could be. Frankly publications don't have time to deal with every new delusional startup thinking they're out there to change the world. Most startups are run of the mill. Give them a juicy story. That's my 2 cents. For the love of marketing, don't try to convince anyone, just help them.

text:
The one thing I love about this group is how we are accepting of all functions tech, non tech Ops etc. I recently DMed someone who works in the Strategy and Ops space launching a community for people iin that space working in those type of roles asking if I could join the group despite being a marketer just so I learn and expand my knowledge but was disappointed to learn its exclusive for strategy and Chief of staff roles.

While understand why this might be the case, it seems slightly close minded to me that you deny someone the opportunity to learn even if its not someone from the same field. Now he did mention they would let me in if they ever open it up for mentoring but it just left a slightly sour taste in my mouth. Maybe I'm looking at this wrong but I feel it would be harmless if someone was genuinely interested in a field and just wanted to learn from people who've been there done that.
